---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Carbide Saw Sharpening | Professional CNC Grinding Services"
  description="Precision carbide saw sharpening with CNC grinding technology. CBN and diamond wheel sharpening for all blade types. Restore OEM specifications and extend blade life."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="gradient-hero text-white py-20">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold mb-6">Carbide Saw Sharpening</h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-blue-100">
          CNC precision grinding with CBN and diamond wheels. Restore your blades to OEM specifications.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="prose-custom">
        <h2>The Material Science of Carbide Sawing</h2>
        <p>
          Carbide-tipped circular saw blades represent the pinnacle of industrial cutting technology. 
          The tungsten carbide tips, bonded to a steel body, provide exceptional hardness and wear resistance 
          for cutting abrasive materials, hardwoods, and non-ferrous metals.
        </p>

        <h3>Precision Tooth Geometry Restoration</h3>
        <p>
          Sharpening is not merely removing metal—it is a controlled material removal process that restores 
          precise geometry. Our CNC grinding systems utilize:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>CBN Grinding Wheels:</strong> For high-speed steel and M42 cobalt blades</li>
          <li><strong>Diamond Wheels:</strong> For carbide-tipped and solid carbide blades</li>
          <li><strong>Flood Coolant Systems:</strong> Prevent thermal damage and maintain temper</li>
          <li><strong>Digital Profile Scanning:</strong> Tooth-by-tooth compensation for wear patterns</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Technical Specifications We Restore</h3>
        <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-xl my-8">
          <table class="w-full">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b-2 border-gray-200">
                <th class="text-left py-3 font-semibold text-primary">Specification</th>
                <th class="text-left py-3 font-semibold text-primary">Description</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-gray-700">
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
                <td class="py-3 font-medium">Rake Angle</td>
                <td class="py-3">Controls cutting aggressiveness and chip formation</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
                <td class="py-3 font-medium">Clearance Angle</td>
                <td class="py-3">Prevents rubbing and heat buildup</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
                <td class="py-3 font-medium">Gullet Depth</td>
                <td class="py-3">Chip evacuation capacity</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-3 font-medium">Hook Angle</td>
                <td class="py-3">Determines feed rate and cut quality</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h3>Carbide Grade Chemistry</h3>
        <p>
          Understanding the material science behind your blades is critical. Carbide grades vary by 
          tungsten carbide to cobalt ratio:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>C-2 Grade (6-10% Cobalt):</strong> Balance of hardness and toughness for general-purpose cutting</li>
          <li><strong>C-3 Grade (4-6% Cobalt):</strong> Harder, more wear-resistant for abrasive materials</li>
          <li><strong>C-4 Grade (2-4% Cobalt):</strong> Extremely hard for non-ferrous metals and high-silica woods</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>The Sharpening Process</h3>
        <p>
          Our multi-step process ensures maximum blade life:
        </p>
        <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-6">
          <li><strong>Inspection:</strong> Digital measurement of current tooth geometry and wear patterns</li>
          <li><strong>Setup:</strong> Precision fixture mounting with tooth-by-tooth indexing</li>
          <li><strong>Grinding:</strong> CNC-controlled material removal to restore original angles</li>
          <li><strong>Setting:</strong> Reset tooth set pattern for proper kerf width</li>
          <li><strong>Tensioning:</strong> Verify blade body tension for straight tracking</li>
          <li><strong>Quality Control:</strong> Final measurement and surface finish inspection</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Maximizing Blade Longevity</h3>
        <p>
          Extend the interval between sharpenings with proper operation:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Match blade grade to material being cut</li>
          <li>Optimize cutting parameters (SFPM and chip load)</li>
          <li>Maintain proper coolant flow and concentration</li>
          <li>Keep machine guides and bearings in specification</li>
          <li>Store blades flat or on proper racks</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="bg-gray-50 py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary mb-4">Ready to Restore Your Blades?</h2>
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 mb-8">
        Contact us for a service quote or technical consultation.
      </p>
      <a href="/carbidesaws-rebuild/contact" class="bg-secondary text-white font-bold px-8 py-4 rounded-lg hover:bg-primary transition inline-flex items-center">
        Get a Quote
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
